25|$|The {{first strike}} in the <b>iron</b> <b>and</b> <b>steel</b> <b>industry</b> in the United States took place among puddlers in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, from December 20, 1849, to May 12, 1850. The {{employers}} broke the strike by cutting wages and hiring new puddlers. Labor {{relations in the}} <b>iron</b> <b>and</b> <b>steel</b> <b>industry</b> remained tense {{for much of the}} next decade. Wages plunged during the Panic of 1857, and the steel industry was slow to recover.|$|E
50|$|In {{the churchyard}} is {{the grave of}} David Mushet (1772-1847), a noted Scottish metallurgist, who built Darkhill Ironworks and who, with his son, greatly {{advanced}} the <b>iron</b> <b>and</b> <b>steel</b> <b>industries.</b>|$|R
